Patch summary:
Carry AOSP's Android/gfxstream build integration forward to the Mesa 26.1.5
release while retaining the guest fixes required by Ika's Apple Silicon path.
The Soong files are generated from Mesa's Meson definitions with
meson2hermetic 9217da54f71a and cover gfxstream and lavapipe for Android x86,
x86_64, and arm64 plus the corresponding host tools. The unrelated physical
Freedreno/Turnip configuration is intentionally omitted from this Cuttlefish
ROM build. Remove Mesa's obsolete Android.mk/Meson cross-build path so Android
16's Soong denylist cannot reject the project before the generated build runs.

Preserve imported AHardwareBuffer layouts for synchronization2 barriers, keep
native DRM-format-modifier queries on the host pass-through path, complete the
BGRA AHardwareBuffer mappings used by Android cursor planes, and expose the
Vulkan 1.4/profile capabilities supported by the generated gfxstream protocol.
The Android Vulkan CPU-only profile's EAC transfer bits remain supplied by the
guest where required.

Expand descriptor push templates into typed vkCmdPushDescriptorSet writes
instead of serializing opaque pData as one byte, which deterministically
crashes the host renderer for mutable sampler templates. Preserve template
stride and guest buffer-handle translation and route the Vulkan 1.4 and KHR
aliases through the same implementation. Let the host fill complete standalone
driver/ID properties, keep legacy and Properties2 format overrides consistent,
mask unsupported video and protected-pipeline capabilities, reject attempts to
enable the masked protected-pipeline feature, emulate LOW/MEDIUM global priority
while denying privileged requests consistently, and fully unwind partially
initialized guest/host devices on allocation failures.

Let Soong and Meson generate gfxstream's reserved-marshalling sources from the
same 26.1.5 Vulkan registry used by the encoder. Carrying an older generated
header here shadows Soong's output and drops newer maintenance6 declarations.

Route the Vulkan 1.4 and KHR map-memory2 entry points through the guest memory
tracker just like legacy vkMapMemory. Autogenerated opaque-pointer marshalling
otherwise returns a host virtual address to the guest and crashes on first use.

Preserve Vulkan maintenance6 per-binding status results. The legacy gfxstream
wire protocol does not return host-written VkBindMemoryStatus values, so split
only status-bearing bind batches into individual calls, record every result,
and retain the original batched fast path when status reporting is not used.

Keep VK_EXT_device_memory_report entirely guest-emulated. Callback pointers are
guest addresses and must never enter the host wire chain; register them with the
guest ResourceTracker after device creation instead. Report the backing memory
heap index rather than the memory-type index in allocation callbacks.

Written against Mesa 26.1.5 (6a02618ccf6c5651ecb9cccbde571eb61fd73592).

